[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] In computer science and graph theory, the term **color-coding** refers to an algorithmic technique which is useful in the discovery of network motifs.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] For example, it can be used to detect a simple path of length k in a given graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] The traditional color-coding algorithm is probabilistic, but it can be derandomized without much overhead in the running time.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Color-coding also applies to the detection of cycles of a given length, and more generally it applies to the subgraph isomorphism problem (an NP-complete problem), where it yields polynomial time algorithms when the subgraph pattern that it is trying to detect has bounded treewidth.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] The color-coding method was proposed and analyzed in 1994 by Noga Alon, Raphael Yuster, and Uri Zwick.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Here, a graph is colorful if every vertex in it is colored with a distinct color.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] This method works by repeating (1) random coloring a graph and (2) finding colorful copy of the target subgraph, and eventually the target subgraph can be found if the process is repeated a sufficient number of times.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Suppose a copy of H in G becomes colorful with some non-zero probability p.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] It immediately follows that if the random coloring is repeated ⁠1/*p*⁠ times, then this copy is expected to become colorful once.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Note that though p is small, it is shown that if $|V_{H}|=O(\log |V|)$ , p is only polynomially small.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Suppose again there exists an algorithm such that, given a graph G and a coloring which maps each vertex of G to one of the k colors, it finds a copy of colorful H, if one exists, within some runtime *O*(*r*).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Then the expected time to find a copy of H in G, if one exists, is $O({\tfrac {r}{p}})$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Sometimes it is also desirable to use a more restricted version of colorfulness.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] For example, in the context of finding cycles in planar graphs, it is possible to develop an algorithm that finds well-colored cycles.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Here, a cycle is well-colored if its vertices are colored by consecutive colors.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] An example would be finding a simple cycle of length k in graph *G* = (*V*, *E*).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] By applying random coloring method, each simple cycle has a probability of $k!/k^{k}>e^{-k}$ to become colorful, since there are $k^{k}$ ways of coloring the k vertices on the cycle, among which there are $k!$ colorful occurrences.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Then an algorithm (described next) can be used to find colorful cycles in the randomly colored graph G in time $O(V^{\omega })$ , where $\omega$ is the matrix multiplication constant.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Therefore, it takes $e^{k}\cdot O(V^{\omega })$ overall time to find a simple cycle of length k in G.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] The colorful cycle-finding algorithm works by first finding all pairs of vertices in V that are connected by a simple path of length *k* − 1, and then checking whether the two vertices in each pair are connected.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Given a coloring function *c* : *V* → {1, ..., *k*} to color graph G, enumerate all partitions of the color set {1, ..., *k*} into two subsets *C*1, *C*2 of size $k/2$ each.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Note that V can be divided into *V*1 and *V*2 accordingly, and let *G*1 and *G*2 denote the subgraphs induced by *V*1 and *V*2 respectively.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Then, recursively find colorful paths of length $k/2-1$ in each of *G*1 and *G*2.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Thus, the recursive relation of matrix multiplications is $t(k)\leq 2^{k}\cdot t(k/2)$ , which yields a runtime of $2^{O(k)}\cdot V^{\omega }$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Although this algorithm finds only the end points of the colorful path, another algorithm by Alon and Naor that finds colorful paths themselves can be incorporated into it.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] The derandomization of color-coding involves enumerating possible colorings of a graph G, such that the randomness of coloring G is no longer required.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] For the target subgraph H in G to be discoverable, the enumeration has to include at least one instance where the H is colorful.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] To achieve this, enumerating a k-perfect family F of hash functions from {1, ..., |*V*|} to {1, ..., *k*} is sufficient.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] By definition, F is k-perfect if for every subset S of {1, ..., |*V*|} where $|S|=k$ , there exists a hash function h in F such that *h* : *S* → {1, ..., *k*} is perfect.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] In other words, there must exist a hash function in F that colors any given k vertices with k distinct colors.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Another explicit construction by Jeanette P.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Schmidt and Alan Siegel yields a family of size $2^{O(k)}\log ^{2}|V|$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Another construction that appears in the original paper of Noga Alon et al. can be obtained by first building a k-perfect family that maps {1, ..., |*V*|} to {1, ..., *k*2}, followed by building another k-perfect family that maps {1, ..., *k*2} to {1, ..., *k*}.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] In the first step, it is possible to construct such a family with 2*n*log *k* random bits that are almost 2log *k*-wise independent, and the sample space needed for generating those random bits can be as small as $k^{O(1)}\log |V|$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] In the second step, it has been shown by Jeanette P.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Schmidt and Alan Siegel that the size of such k-perfect family can be $2^{O(k)}$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Consequently, by composing the k-perfect families from both steps, a k-perfect family of size $2^{O(k)}\log |V|$ that maps from {1, ..., |*V*|} to {1, ..., *k*} can be obtained.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] In the case of derandomizing well-coloring, where each vertex on the subgraph is colored consecutively, a k-perfect family of hash functions from {1, ..., |*V*|} to {1, ..., *k*!} is needed.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] A sufficient k-perfect family which maps from {1, ..., |*V*|} to {1, ..., *kk*} can be constructed in a way similar to the approach 3 above (the first step).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] In particular, it is done by using *nk*log *k* random bits that are almost *k*log *k* independent, and the size of the resulting k-perfect family will be $k^{O(k)}\log |V|$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] The derandomization of color-coding method can be easily parallelized, yielding efficient NC algorithms.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Recently, color-coding has attracted much attention in the field of bioinformatics.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] One example is the detection of signaling pathways in protein-protein interaction (PPI) networks.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Another example is to discover and to count the number of motifs in PPI networks.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Studying both signaling pathways and motifs allows a deeper understanding of the similarities and differences of many biological functions, processes, and structures among organisms.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Due to the huge amount of gene data that can be collected, searching for pathways or motifs can be highly time consuming.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] However, by exploiting the color-coding method, the motifs or signaling pathways with $k=O(\log n)$ vertices in a network G with n vertices can be found very efficiently in polynomial time.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/color-coding] Thus, this enables us to explore more complex or larger structures in PPI networks.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] In the mathematical discipline of graph theory, a **feedback vertex set** (FVS) of a graph is a set of vertices whose removal leaves a graph without cycles ("removal" means deleting the vertex and all edges adjacent to it).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] Equivalently, each FVS contains at least one vertex of any cycle in the graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] The **feedback vertex set number** of a graph is the size of a smallest FVS.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] Whether there exists a **feedback vertex set of size at most k** is an NP-complete problem; it was among the first problems shown to be NP-complete.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] It has wide applications in operating systems, database systems, and VLSI chip design.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] The graph $G[V\setminus X]$ that remains after removing X from G is an induced forest (resp. an induced directed acyclic graph in the case of directed graphs).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] Thus, finding a minimum FVS in a graph is equivalent to finding a maximum induced forest (resp. maximum induced directed acyclic graph in the case of directed graphs).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] Karp (1972) showed that finding a feedback vertex set of size $\leq k$ in *directed* graphs is NP-complete.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] The problem remains NP-complete on directed graphs with maximum in-degree and out-degree two, and on directed planar graphs with maximum in-degree and out-degree three.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] Karp's reduction also implies the NP-completeness of the feedback vertex set problem on *undirected* graphs, where the problem stays NP-complete on graphs of maximum degree four.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] The feedback vertex set problem can be solved in polynomial time on graphs of maximum degree at most three, using an algorithm based on the matroid parity problem.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] The corresponding NP optimization problem of finding the size of a minimum feedback vertex set can be solved in time *O*(1.7347*n*), where *n* is the number of vertices in the graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] This algorithm actually computes a maximum induced forest, and when such a forest is obtained, its complement is a minimum feedback vertex set.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] The number of minimal feedback vertex sets in a graph is bounded by *O*(1.8638*n*).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] The directed feedback vertex set problem can still be solved in time *O**(1.9977*n*), where *n* is the number of vertices in the given directed graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] The parameterized versions of the directed and undirected problems are both fixed-parameter tractable.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] In undirected graphs of maximum degree three, the feedback vertex set problem can be solved in polynomial time, by transforming it into an instance of the matroid parity problem for linear matroids.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] The special case of finding all feedback vertices in a directed graph (vertices that lie on every directed cycle) can be solved in linear time using a DFS-based algorithm by Garey and Tarjan.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] The best known approximation algorithm on undirected graphs is by a factor of two.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] By contrast, the directed version of the problem appears to be much harder to approximate.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] Under the unique games conjecture, an unproven but commonly used computational hardness assumption, it is NP-hard to approximate the problem to within any constant factor in polynomial time.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] The same hardness result was originally proven for the closely related feedback arc set problem, but since the feedback arc set problem and feedback vertex set problem in directed graphs are reducible to one another while preserving solution sizes, it also holds for the latter.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/feedback-vertex-set] According to the Erdős–Pósa theorem, the size of a minimum feedback vertex set is within a logarithmic factor of the maximum number of vertex-disjoint cycles in the given graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] In computer science, **parameterized complexity** is a branch of computational complexity theory that focuses on classifying computational problems according to their inherent difficulty with respect to *multiple* parameters of the input or output.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The complexity of a problem is then measured as a function of those parameters.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] This allows the classification of NP-hard problems on a finer scale than in the classical setting, where the complexity of a problem is only measured as a function of the number of bits in the input.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] This appears to have been first demonstrated in Gurevich, Stockmeyer & Vishkin (1984).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The first systematic work on parameterized complexity was done by Downey & Fellows (1999).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] However, some problems can be solved by algorithms that are exponential only in the size of a fixed parameter while polynomial in the size of the input.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Under the assumption that P ≠ NP, there exist many natural problems that require super-polynomial running time when complexity is measured in terms of the input size only but that are computable in a time that is polynomial in the input size and exponential or worse in a parameter k.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Hence, if k is fixed at a small value and the growth of the function over k is relatively small then such problems can still be considered "tractable" despite their traditional classification as "intractable".
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Such an algorithm is called a fixed-parameter tractable (FPT) algorithm, because the problem can be solved efficiently (i.e., in polynomial time) for constant values of the fixed parameter.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A parameterized problem that allows for such an FPT algorithm is said to be a **fixed-parameter tractable** problem and belongs to the class FPT, and the early name of the theory of parameterized complexity was **fixed-parameter tractability**.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Many problems have the following form: given an object x and a nonnegative integer k, does x have some property that depends on k?
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] For instance, for the vertex cover problem, the parameter can be the number of vertices in the cover.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] In many applications, for example when modelling error correction, one can assume the parameter to be "small" compared to the total input size.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Then it is challenging to find an algorithm that is exponential *only* in k, and not in the input size.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] In this way, parameterized complexity can be seen as *two-dimensional* complexity theory.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] when its parameter is the size of the solution to the problem.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] For example, there is an algorithm that solves the vertex cover problem in $O(kn+1.274^{k})$ time, where n is the number of vertices and k is the size of the vertex cover.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] This means that vertex cover is fixed-parameter tractable with the size of the solution as the parameter (its natural parameter).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The class **FPL** (fixed parameter linear) is the class of problems solvable in time $f(k)\cdot |x|$ for some computable function f.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] An example is the Boolean satisfiability problem, parameterised by the number of variables.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A given formula of size m with k variables can be checked by brute force in time $O(2^{k}m)$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A vertex cover of size k in a graph of order n can be found in time $O(2^{k}n)$ , so the vertex cover problem is also in FPL.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] An example of a problem that is thought not to be in FPT is graph coloring parameterised by the number of colors.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] It is known that 3-coloring is NP-hard, and an algorithm for graph k-coloring in time $f(k)n^{O(1)}$ for $k=3$ would run in polynomial time in the size of the input.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Thus, if graph coloring parameterised by the number of colors were in FPT, then P = NP.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] There are a number of alternative definitions of FPT.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] For example, the running-time requirement can be replaced by $f(k)+|x|^{O(1)}$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Also, a parameterised problem is in FPT if it has a so-called kernel.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Kernelization is a preprocessing technique that reduces the original instance to its "hard kernel", a possibly much smaller instance that is equivalent to the original instance but has a size that is bounded by a function in the parameter.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] FPT is closed under a parameterised notion of reductions called ***fpt-reductions***.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Obviously, FPT contains all polynomial-time computable problems.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Moreover, it contains all optimisation problems in NP that allow an efficient polynomial-time approximation scheme (EPTAS).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] These problems are called slicewise polynomial, in the sense that each "slice" of fixed *k* has a polynomial-time algorithm, although with a possibly different exponent for each *k*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Compare this with FPT, which merely allows a different constant prefactor for each value of k.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] XP strictly contains FPT by diagonalization.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A problem is **para-NP-hard** if it is ${\textsf {NP}}$ -hard already for a constant value of the parameter.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] That is, there is a "slice" of fixed k that is ${\textsf {NP}}$ -hard.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A parameterized problem that is ${\textsf {para-NP}}$ -hard cannot belong to the class ${\textsf {XP}}$ , unless ${\textsf {P}}={\textsf {NP}}$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A classic example of a ${\textsf {para-NP}}$ -hard parameterized problem is graph coloring, parameterized by the number k of colors, which is already ${\textsf {NP}}$ -hard for $k=3$ (see Graph coloring#Computational complexity).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] In the parameterized complexity theory, there are some hierarchies of complexity classes.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Each such class is closed under fpt-reduction.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The most important ones are the ***W* hierarchy** and the ***A* hierarchy**.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] In general, there are two ways to define a complexity class: machine-theoretically and logically.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] In machine theory, a class is defined as the set of decision problems solvable by a class of machines.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] In logic, a class is defined as the set of decision problems definable by a class of logical formulas.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The **Hamming weight** (**weight** for short) of a binary string is the number of ones appearing in it.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A Boolean circuit is an acyclic directed graph where the nodes are one of the following gates: AND, OR, NOT.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A small gate is a gate with fan-in 0, 1, or 2.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The **weft** is the largest number of big gates achievable on any path from an input to the output.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The **depth** is the largest number of gates (small or big) achievable on any path from an input to the output.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A Boolean circuit is **monotone** iff it uses no NOT gate.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A Boolean circuit is **antimonotone** iff it is of the form $\phi (\neg x_{1},\dots ,\neg x_{n})$ where $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ are all its inputs, and $\phi$ is monotone.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] we define $\operatorname {p-MC} (\Gamma )$ to be the **parameterized model checking** problem for this tuple.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Here we see that "W" stands for "weight".
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Note that in the above definition, $w,d$ are independent of $(x,k)$ , but the circuit itself depends on $(x,k)$ , and may change if one changes either x or k .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A **normalized circuit** of weft *w* and depth *d* is a circuit, where the first $d-w$ layers contain only small gates, and the last w layers contain alternating big gates of AND and OR.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] One can iterate the associative laws and de Morgan distribution laws to normalize the circuit in fpt-time.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Therefore, without loss of generality, we can consider only normalized circuits.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Model-theoretically, the class *W[t]* is defined as the class of problems fpt-reducible to $\operatorname {p-MC} (\Sigma _{t,1})$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] While the *W* hierarchy is a hierarchy contained in NP, the *A* hierarchy more closely mimics the polynomial-time hierarchy from classical complexity.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Machine-theoretically, the A hierarchy of problems are defined as problems that are fpt-reducible to computations by certain kinds of alternating Turing machines.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Model-theoretically, the class *A[t]* is defined as the class of problems fpt-reducible to $\operatorname {p-MC} (\Sigma _{t})$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] For example, the *k*-clique problem can be specified as a model checking problem.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The language has a single binary relation E , where $E(x,y)$ means " $x,y$ share an edge".
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Then, a finite model A is a graph, and it has a *k*-clique iff $A\models \phi _{k}$ , where $\phi _{k}:=\exists x_{1:k},\bigwedge _{1\leq i<j\leq n}E(x_{i},x_{j})$ This shows that the *k*-clique problem is in $A[1]$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A problem is ***A[i]*-complete** if it is *A[i]*, and any *A[i]* problem fpt-reduces to it.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Intuitively, problems in W[1] class can be interpreted of the form: Is there an object of size *k* with a certain locally-checkable property?
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] That is, a big AND over many OR of fan-in 2.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Note that the plain nonblocker problem is FPT.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Note on the nondeterministic Turing machine.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The machine may be specified by one of any of the standard formulations.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] One usually considers the one-tape Turing machine, but the short Turing machine problem remains *W[1]* even if we allow with *f*(*k*) tapes and even *f*(*k*) of *f*(*k*)-dimensional tapes, but even with this extension, the restriction to *f*(*k*) tape alphabet size is FPT.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Crucially, because the machine *M* itself is part of the problem input, the input size *n* is bigger than the number of states of *M*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] In this way, the Turing machine can take one of n possible computation paths per step, accessing $n^{O(k)}$ steps in total within time *k*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Thus, we see that *W[1]* is not obviously contained within *FPT*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The independent set problem can be encoded thus.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Given each graph $(V,E)$ , its independent set problem is encoded by the following weft-1 Boolean circuit: $\Phi _{\text{IS}}(V,E):=\bigwedge _{\{u,v\}\in E}(\neg x_{u}\lor \neg x_{v})$ where E is the set of edges in the graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The graph has an independent set of size *k* iff there is a weight-*k* input to its Boolean circuit, such that it outputs 1.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The clique problem can be coded as $\Phi _{\text{clique}}(V,E):=\bigwedge _{\{u,v\}\subset V,u\neq v,\{u,v\}\not \in E}(\neg x_{u}\lor \neg x_{v})$ It checks that any pair vertices that don't make an edge cannot be chosen, so any chosen set of vertices is forced to be a clique.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The short Turing machine problem can be converted to a Boolean formula using the same proof idea as of the Cook–Levin theorem, which shows SAT is NP-complete by coding Turing machine computational traces as Boolean formulas.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Of the indices, time *t* and tape position *p* range over *1:k*, The ranges of the indices to the Turing machine state *i, j*, transition *m*, and symbols *a, b* are determined by the description of the machine M, but they are both bounded within *1:n*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] A computational trace through the Turing machine is then fully specified by setting *k* variables of $s_{t,i,j,a,b}$ to True to indicate the Turing machine state transitions at each time, and setting $k^{2}$ variables of $y_{t,p,a,b}$ to True to indicate the tape state transition at each time.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] This reduces the short Turing machine problem to a problem of finding a weight- $(k+k^{2})$ satisfying assignment to a weft-1, depth-2, antimonotone Boolean circuit.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The dominating set problem has formula $\Psi _{\text{dom}}(V,E)=\bigwedge _{u\in V}\bigvee _{v\in \operatorname {Neighbor} [u]}x_{v}$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Some problems are known to be *W[i]*-complete, though they are in a computationally generic form, and are usually studied within parameterized complexity theory itself.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Empirically, as of 2013, almost all naturally-occurring parameterized problems that they have studied, turned out to be *W[0]*-complete, *W[1]*-complete, or *W[2]*-complete.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] These problems are essentially "artificial", in that they are not studied except within the context of parameterized complexity.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] It contains *W[SAT]*, since a Boolean formula can be efficiently converted to a Boolean circuit.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Note that the opposite is not true in general, since the equivalent Boolean formula to a Boolean circuit may be necessarily exponentially larger than the circuit.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Equivalently, it is the class of problems that can be decided by a nondeterministic $h(k)\cdot {|x|}^{O(1)}$ -time Turing machine that makes at most $O(f(k)\cdot \log n)$ nondeterministic choices in the computation on $(x,k)$ (a *k*-restricted Turing machine).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] It is known that FPT is contained in W[P], and the inclusion is believed to be strict.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] However, resolving this issue would imply a solution to the P versus NP problem.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The *W** hierarchy is similar to the *W* hierarchy, but it parameterizes depth, rather than holding it constant.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] One can interpret this as a 2-player game, with the first player trying to make the circuit output True, and the second player trying to make the circuit output False.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The first player makes a move by setting exactly $k_{1}$ inputs of $I_{1}$ to True and the others to False, then the second player makes a move on $I_{2}$ , etc.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] The circuit is under alternating weight- $(k_{1},\dots ,k_{r})$ conditions iff player 1 has a winning strategy.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] It turns out that the hierarchy collapses: $AW[1]=AW[2]=\cdots$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/fixed-parameter-tractability] Thus, the literature writes just a common symbol for them: $AW[\ast ]:=AW[1]=AW[2]=\cdots$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] The technique was invented by Reed, Smith and Vetta to show that the odd cycle transversal problem was solvable in time *O*(3*k* *kmn*), for a graph with n vertices, m edges, and odd cycle transversal number k.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] Odd cycle transversal is the problem of finding the smallest set of vertices of a graph that includes at least one vertex from every odd cycle; its parameterized complexity was a longstanding open question.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] This technique later proved very useful in showing fixed-parameter tractability results.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] It is now considered to be one of the fundamental techniques in the area of parameterized algorithmics.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] Iterative compression has been used successfully in many problems, for instance odd cycle transversal (see below) and edge bipartization, feedback vertex set, and cluster vertex deletion.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] It has also been used successfully for exact exponential time algorithms for independent set.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] Iterative compression applies, for instance, to parameterized graph problems whose inputs are a graph *G* = (*V*,*E*) and a natural number k, and where the problem is to test the existence of a solution (a set of vertices) of size ≤ *k*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] This algorithm calls the compression subroutine a linear number of times.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] Therefore, if the compression variant is solvable in fixed-parameter tractable time, i.e., *f*(*k*) · *n**c* for some constant *c*, then the iterative compression procedure solving the entire problem runs in *f*(*k*) · *n**c*+1 time.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] The same technique can be applied to finding sets of edges for graph properties closed under subgraphs (rather than induced subgraph), or for other properties beyond graph theory.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] When the value of the parameter k is unknown, it can be found by using an outer level of exponential search or sequential search for the optimal choice of k, with each step of the search based on the same iterative compression algorithm.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] An odd cycle transversal of a graph is a set of vertices which can be deleted to make the graph bipartite.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] In their original paper, Reed et al. gave an iterative compression algorithm to determine if a graph has an odd cycle transversal of size at most *k*, in time *O*(3*k* *kmn*).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] Later, a simpler algorithm was given, also using iterative compression, by Lokshstanov, Saurabh and Sikdar.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] Once these three sets have been selected, the remaining vertices of a deletion set X (if it exists) can be found from them by applying a max-flow min-cut algorithm.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] Vertex cover is another example for which iterative compression can be employed.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] In the vertex cover problem, a graph *G* = (*V*,*E*) and a natural number k are taken as inputs and the algorithm must decide whether there exists a set X of k vertices such that every edge is incident to a vertex in X.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] In the compression variant of the problem, the input is a set Y of *k* + 1 vertices that are incident to all edges of the graph, and the algorithm must find a set X of size k with the same property, if it exists.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] One way to do this is to test all 2*k* + 1 choices of which subset of Y is to be removed from the cover and reintroduced back into the graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] Such a choice can only work if no two removed vertices are adjacent, and for each such choice, the subroutine must include in the cover all the vertices outside Y that are incident to an edge that becomes uncovered by this removal.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/iterative-compression] Using this subroutine in an iterative compression algorithm gives a simple *O*(2*k* *n*2) algorithm for vertex cover.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] In graph theory and theoretical computer science, the **longest path problem** is the problem of finding a simple path of maximum length in a given graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] A path is called *simple* if it does not have any repeated vertices; the length of a path may either be measured by its number of edges, or (in weighted graphs) by the sum of the weights of its edges.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] In contrast to the shortest path problem, which can be solved in polynomial time in graphs without negative-weight cycles, the longest path problem is NP-hard and the decision version of the problem, which asks whether a path exists of at least some given length, is NP-complete.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] This means that the decision problem cannot be solved in polynomial time for arbitrary graphs unless P = NP.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Stronger hardness results are also known showing that it is difficult to approximate.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] However, it has a linear time solution for directed acyclic graphs, which has important applications in finding the critical path in scheduling problems.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] The NP-hardness of the unweighted longest path problem can be shown using a reduction from the Hamiltonian path problem: a graph *G* has a Hamiltonian path if and only if its longest path has length *n* − 1, where *n* is the number of vertices in *G*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Because the Hamiltonian path problem is NP-complete, this reduction shows that the decision version of the longest path problem is also NP-complete.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] In this decision problem, the input is a graph *G* and a number *k*; the desired output is *yes* if *G* contains a path of *k* or more edges, and *no* otherwise.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] If the longest path problem could be solved in polynomial time, it could be used to solve this decision problem, by finding a longest path and then comparing its length to the number *k*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Therefore, the longest path problem is NP-hard.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] The question "does there exist a simple path in a given graph with at least *k* edges" is NP-complete.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] In weighted complete graphs with non-negative edge weights, the weighted longest path problem is the same as the Travelling salesman path problem, because the longest path always includes all vertices.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] A longest path between two given vertices *s* and *t* in a weighted graph *G* is the same thing as a shortest path in a graph −*G* derived from *G* by changing every weight to its negation.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Therefore, if shortest paths can be found in −*G*, then longest paths can also be found in *G*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] For most graphs, this transformation is not useful because it creates cycles of negative length in −*G*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] But if *G* is a directed acyclic graph (DAG), then no negative cycles can be created, and a longest path in *G* can be found in linear time by applying a linear time algorithm for shortest paths in −*G*, which is also a directed acyclic graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] For a DAG, the longest path from a source vertex to all other vertices can be obtained by running the shortest-path algorithm on −*G*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] For each vertex *v* of the DAG, in the topological ordering, compute the length of the longest path ending at *v* by looking at its incoming neighbors and adding one to the maximum length recorded for those neighbors.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] If *v* has no incoming neighbors, set the length of the longest path ending at *v* to zero.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] In either case, record this number so that later steps of the algorithm can access it.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Once this has been done, the longest path in the whole DAG may be obtained by starting at the vertex *v* with the largest recorded value, then repeatedly stepping backwards to its incoming neighbor with the largest recorded value, and reversing the sequence of vertices found in this way.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] This is equivalent to running the shortest-path algorithm on −*G*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] In such a graph, the longest path from the first milestone to the last one is the critical path, which describes the total time for completing the project.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Longest paths of directed acyclic graphs may also be applied in layered graph drawing: assigning each vertex *v* of a directed acyclic graph *G* to the layer whose number is the length of the longest path ending at *v* results in a layer assignment for *G* with the minimum possible number of layers.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Björklund, Husfeldt & Khanna (2004) write that the longest path problem in unweighted undirected graphs "is notorious for the difficulty of understanding its approximation hardness".
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] The best polynomial time approximation algorithm known for this case achieves only a very weak approximation ratio, $n/\exp(\Omega ({\sqrt {\log n}}))$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] In the case of unweighted but directed graphs, strong inapproximability results are known.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] For every $\epsilon >0$ the problem cannot be approximated to within a factor of $n^{1-\epsilon }$ unless P = NP, and with stronger complexity-theoretic assumptions it cannot be approximated to within a factor of $n/\log ^{2+\epsilon }n$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] The color-coding technique can be used to find paths of logarithmic length, if they exist, but this gives an approximation ratio of only $O(n/\log n)$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] The longest path problem is fixed-parameter tractable when parameterized by the length of the path.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Use the sequence of root-to-leaf paths of the depth-first search tree, in the order in which they were traversed by the search, to construct a path decomposition of the graph, with pathwidth d .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Apply dynamic programming to this path decomposition to find a longest path in time $O(d!2^{d}n)$ , where n is the number of vertices in the graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Since the output path has length at least as large as d , the running time is also bounded by $O(\ell !2^{\ell }n)$ , where $\ell$ is the length of the longest path.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Using color-coding, the dependence on path length can be reduced to singly exponential.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] A similar dynamic programming technique shows that the longest path problem is also fixed-parameter tractable when parameterized by the treewidth of the graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] For graphs of bounded clique-width, the longest path can also be solved by a polynomial time dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] However, the exponent of the polynomial depends on the clique-width of the graph, so this algorithms is not fixed-parameter tractable.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] The longest path problem, parameterized by clique-width, is hard for the parameterized complexity class $W[1]$ , showing that a fixed-parameter tractable algorithm is unlikely to exist.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] A linear-time algorithm for finding a longest path in a tree was proposed by Edsger Dijkstra around 1960, while a formal proof of this algorithm was published in 2002.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Furthermore, a longest path can be computed in polynomial time on weighted trees, on block graphs, on cacti, on bipartite permutation graphs, and on Ptolemaic graphs.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] For the class of interval graphs, an $O(n^{4})$ -time algorithm is known, which uses a dynamic programming approach.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] The latter algorithm is based on special properties of the lexicographic depth first search (LDFS) vertex ordering of co-comparability graphs.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] For co-comparability graphs also an alternative polynomial-time algorithm with higher running time $O(n^{7})$ is known, which is based on the Hasse diagram of the partially ordered set defined by the complement of the input co-comparability graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Furthermore, the longest path problem is solvable in polynomial time on any class of graphs with bounded treewidth or bounded clique-width, such as the distance-hereditary graphs.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] Finally, it is clearly NP-hard on all graph classes on which the Hamiltonian path problem is NP-hard, such as on split graphs, circle graphs, and planar graphs.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] A simple model of a directed acyclic graph is the Price model, developed by Derek J. de Solla Price to represent citation networks.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] This is simple enough to allow for analytic results to be found for some properties.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/longest-path-problem] For instance, the length of the longest path, from the n-th node added to the network to the first node in the network, scales as $\ln(n)$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] In graph theory, a **vertex cover** (sometimes **node cover**) of a graph is a set of vertices that includes at least one endpoint of every edge of the graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] In computer science, the problem of finding a **minimum vertex cover** is a classical optimization problem.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] It is NP-hard, so it cannot be solved by a polynomial-time algorithm if P ≠ NP.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Moreover, it is hard to approximate – it cannot be approximated up to a factor smaller than 2 if the unique games conjecture is true.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] On the other hand, it has several simple 2-factor approximations.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] It is a typical example of an NP-hard optimization problem that has an approximation algorithm.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Its decision version, the **vertex cover problem**, was one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems and is therefore a classical NP-complete problem in computational complexity theory.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Furthermore, the vertex cover problem is fixed-parameter tractable and a central problem in parameterized complexity theory.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The minimum vertex cover problem can be formulated as a half-integral, linear program whose dual linear program is the maximum matching problem.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Vertex cover problems have been generalized to hypergraphs, see *Vertex cover in hypergraphs*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Formally, a vertex cover $V'$ of an undirected graph $G=(V,E)$ is a subset of V such that $(uv\in E)\Rightarrow (u\in V'\lor v\in V')$ , that is to say it is a set of vertices $V'$ where every edge has at least one endpoint in the vertex cover $V'$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Such a set is said to *cover* the edges of G .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The upper figure shows two examples of vertex covers, with some vertex cover $V'$ marked in red.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] A *minimum vertex cover* is a vertex cover of smallest possible size.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The vertex cover number $\tau$ is the size of a minimum vertex cover, i.e. $\tau =|V'|$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The lower figure shows examples of minimum vertex covers in the previous graphs.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The **minimum vertex cover problem** is the optimization problem of finding a smallest vertex cover in a given graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] They are equivalent under polynomial-time reduction by using binary search.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The vertex cover problem is an NP-complete problem: it was one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] It is often used in computational complexity theory as a starting point for NP-hardness proofs.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Assume that every vertex has an associated cost of $c(v)\geq 0$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The (weighted) minimum vertex cover problem can be formulated as the following integer linear program (ILP).
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] This ILP belongs to the more general class of ILPs for covering problems.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The integrality gap of this ILP is 2 , so its relaxation (allowing each variable to be in the interval from 0 to 1, rather than requiring the variables to be only 0 or 1) gives a factor- 2 approximation algorithm for the minimum vertex cover problem.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Furthermore, the linear programming relaxation of that ILP is *half-integral*, that is, there exists an optimal solution for which each entry $x_{v}$ is either 0, 1/2, or 1.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] A 2-approximate vertex cover can be obtained from this fractional solution by selecting the subset of vertices whose variables are nonzero.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The decision variant of the vertex cover problem is NP-complete, which means it is unlikely that there is an efficient algorithm to solve it exactly for arbitrary graphs.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] NP-completeness can be proven by reduction from 3-satisfiability or, as Karp did, by reduction from the clique problem.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Vertex cover remains NP-complete even in cubic graphs and even in planar graphs of degree at most 3.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] For bipartite graphs, the equivalence between vertex cover and maximum matching described by Kőnig's theorem allows the bipartite vertex cover problem to be solved in polynomial time.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] For tree graphs, an algorithm finds a minimal vertex cover in polynomial time by finding the first leaf in the tree and adding its parent to the minimal vertex cover, then deleting the leaf and parent and all associated edges and continuing repeatedly until no edges remain in the tree.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] An exhaustive search algorithm can solve the problem in time 2*k**n**O*(1), where *k* is the size of the vertex cover.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Vertex cover is therefore fixed-parameter tractable, and if we are only interested in small *k*, we can solve the problem in polynomial time.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] One algorithmic technique that works here is called *bounded search tree algorithm*, and its idea is to repeatedly choose some vertex and recursively branch, with two cases at each step: place either the current vertex or all its neighbours into the vertex cover.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The algorithm for solving vertex cover that achieves the best asymptotic dependence on the parameter runs in time $O(1.2738^{k}+(k\cdot n))$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The klam value of this time bound (an estimate for the largest parameter value that could be solved in a reasonable amount of time) is approximately 190.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] That is, unless additional algorithmic improvements can be found, this algorithm is suitable only for instances whose vertex cover number is 190 or less.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Under reasonable complexity-theoretic assumptions, namely the exponential time hypothesis, the running time cannot be improved to 2*o*(*k*), even when n is $O(k)$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] However, for planar graphs, and more generally, for graphs excluding some fixed graph as a minor, a vertex cover of size *k* can be found in time *$2^{O({\sqrt {k}})}n^{O(1)}$*, i.e., the problem is subexponential fixed-parameter tractable.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] This algorithm is again optimal, in the sense that, under the exponential time hypothesis, no algorithm can solve vertex cover on planar graphs in time *$2^{o({\sqrt {k}})}n^{O(1)}$*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] One can find a factor-2 approximation by repeatedly taking *both* endpoints of an edge into the vertex cover, then removing them from the graph.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Put otherwise, we find a maximal matching *M* with a greedy algorithm and construct a vertex cover *C* that consists of all endpoints of the edges in *M*.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] In the following figure, a maximal matching *M* is marked with red, and the vertex cover *C* is marked with blue.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The set *C* constructed this way is a vertex cover: suppose that an edge *e* is not covered by *C*; then *M* ∪ {*e*} is a matching and *e* ∉ *M*, which is a contradiction with the assumption that *M* is maximal.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Furthermore, if *e* = {*u*, *v*} ∈ *M*, then any vertex cover – including an optimal vertex cover – must contain *u* or *v* (or both); otherwise the edge *e* is not covered.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] That is, an optimal cover contains at least *one* endpoint of each edge in *M*; in total, the set *C* is at most 2 times as large as the optimal vertex cover.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] This simple algorithm was discovered independently by Fanica Gavril and Mihalis Yannakakis.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] More involved techniques show that there are approximation algorithms with a slightly better approximation factor.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] For example, an approximation algorithm with an approximation factor of ${\textstyle 2-\Theta \left(1/{\sqrt {\log |V|}}\right)}$ is known.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The problem can be approximated with an approximation factor $2/(1+\delta )$ in $\delta$ - dense graphs.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] No better constant-factor approximation algorithm than the above one is known.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] The minimum vertex cover problem is APX-complete, that is, it cannot be approximated arbitrarily well unless **P** = **NP**.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Using techniques from the PCP theorem, Dinur and Safra proved in 2005 that minimum vertex cover cannot be approximated within a factor of 1.3606 for any sufficiently large vertex degree unless **P** = **NP**.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Later, the factor was improved to ${\sqrt {2}}-\epsilon$ for any $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Moreover, if the unique games conjecture is true then minimum vertex cover cannot be approximated within any constant factor better than 2.
[src:fixed-parameter-tractable/vertex-cover] Although finding the minimum-size vertex cover is equivalent to finding the maximum-size independent set, as described above, the two problems are not equivalent in an approximation-preserving way: The Independent Set problem has *no* constant-factor approximation unless **P** = **NP**.
